<caption>"What Do Prices 'Know' That You Don't?" by the Institute for Humane Studies</caption></figure></para><para id="eip-270"><title>Watch on YouTube</title><link url="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WPy-QKXofQs" window="new">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WPy-QKXofQs</link></para></section><section id="eip-307"><title>Exercises</title><exercise id="eip-866"><problem id="eip-741">
  <para id="eip-758"><list id="write-numbers-list" mark-suffix=":" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha"><title>How was Moe Cashferme able to determine which crop was most demanded by society? By:</title><item>researching what crops are best for society</item> 
  <item>paying attention to the crop in which consumers paid the highest price</item> 
  <item>consulting with friends and family members</item>
  <item>making a lucky guess</item></list></para></problem>

<solution id="eip-822">
  <para id="eip-852">c:	consulting with friends and family members
  </para></solution>
</exercise><exercise id="eip-958"><problem id="eip-116">
  <para id="eip-496"><list id="writenumberslist" mark-suffix=":" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha"><title>When individuals are directed by prices determined in competitive markets, their actions will tend to promote the productive use of resources:</title><item>only if buyers and sellers personally care about economic efficiency</item> 
  <item>even when each market participant cares only about their own self-interest rather than the overall efficiency of resource use</item> 
  <item>even if business firms fail to produce goods efficiently</item>
  <item>if, and only if, businesses recognize their social obligation to keep costs low and use resources wisely</item></list></para></problem>

<solution id="eip-70">
  <para id="eip-857">b:	even when each market participant cares only about their own self-interest rather than the overall efficiency of resource use.
  </para></solution></exercise></section></content>

